  "signature": "ed25519:b4e2d1f3a5c7e9b1d3f5a7c9e1b3d5f7a9c1e3b5d7f9a1c3e5b7d9f1a3c5e7b9",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/sqa-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2023R2) is a commercially validated platform with documented V&V reports. Version control, change management, and regression test suites are maintained under ISO 9001 QMS. Software release notes confirm no known defects affecting rotating machinery hemolysis predictions. Gradation 2 achieved: solver has documented SQA procedures and traceable version history consistent with MRL 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/code-verification-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Order-of-accuracy tests were performed using manufactured solutions for the incompressible Navier-Stokes equations. Observed convergence rates match theoretical second-order accuracy for the finite-volume discretization. Benchmark comparisons against the FDA nozzle and backward-facing step canonical cases confirm solver implementation correctness. Gradation 2 achieved: formal order-of-accuracy verification completed with documented results."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/discretization-error-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted following ASME V&V 20 GCI methodology. Meshes of 4.2M, 12.1M, and 31.8M cells were evaluated. Grid Convergence Index for the primary QoI (volume-averaged shear stress) is 1.8%, below the 5% threshold. Richardson extrapolation confirms near-asymptotic convergence. The production mesh (12.1M cells) was selected balancing accuracy and computational cost. Achieves Gradation 3, exceeding the MRL 2 requirement of Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions are documented with calibrated instrumentation. Flow rates measured with Coriolis mass flowmeter (±0.5% accuracy). Rotational speed controlled via closed-loop feedback (±5 RPM). Temperature maintained at 37°C ± 0.5°C using recirculating bath. Inlet pressure measured with calibrated transducers. All five operating points (2–6 L/min at 2500–3500 RPM) are within the device's intended clinical operating envelope. Gradation 2 achieved: test conditions are quantified with traceable uncertainty budgets."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values are compared against experimental measurements across all five operating points. Mean absolute percentage error is 8.3%, within the pre-specified 15% acceptance threshold. Relative hemolysis index RH < 1 for all worst-case conditions. Systematic trend agreement confirmed: model correctly identifies the 4 L/min, 3000 RPM condition as highest hemolysis. Gradation 2 achieved: quantitative comparison with documented acceptance threshold."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) computed via the power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen et al., modified Heuser-Opitz). This QoI directly maps to the clinical outcome of red blood cell damage. Secondary QoIs include volume-averaged shear stress, exposure time distribution, and pressure head. All QoIs are directly traceable to the COU decision criterion (RH < 1 vs. predicate). Gradation 2 achieved: QoIs are formally defined and linked to clinical decision criterion."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation activities were performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is geometrically representative of the Class II CPB device under assessment. Operating conditions span the intended clinical range. Blood analog fluid (glycerol-water, matched viscosity at 37°C) was used in experiments, with Newtonian assumption justified by high-shear conditions. The validation hierarchy progresses from component-level (impeller flow) to system-level (hemolysis index), providing adequate coverage for MRL 2. Gradation 2 achieved: validation activities are demonstrably relevant to the COU geometry and operating conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-scopeout-criteria",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, separate characterization of numerical solver error beyond code verification and discretization error is not required. Iterative convergence is monitored via residual drop to 1e-6 for all transport equations and confirmed through QoI stabilization plots. Round-off error is negligible for double-precision arithmetic at the mesh sizes employed. Scoped out per ASME V&V 40 Table 3 for MRL 2 with documented justification."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-scopeout-criteria",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment is scoped out at MRL 2 per ASME V&V 40 Table 3. Simulation execution is performed by trained CFD engineers following documented standard operating procedures. Boundary condition setup, turbulence model selection, and post-processing scripts are version-controlled and peer-reviewed prior to submission. No evidence of systematic user-induced errors identified during independent review. Scoped out with documented procedural controls."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-scopeout-criteria",
      "rationale": "Formal model form uncertainty quantification is scoped out at MRL 2. The k-omega SST turbulence model is selected based on literature consensus for rotating blood pump applications and confirmed by the validation comparison (8.3% MAPE). The Newtonian blood assumption is justified by predominance of high-shear regions (>50 s-1) in the impeller passage. Hemolysis power-law constants are taken from peer-reviewed literature with documented provenance. Scoped out per MRL 2 requirements with qualitative justification documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-inputs-scopeout-criteria",
      "rationale": "Formal sensitivity analysis of model inputs is scoped out at MRL 2. Key inputs (geometry, boundary conditions, fluid properties) are derived from calibrated measurements with documented uncertainty. Geometry is reconstructed from CMM measurements with ±0.05 mm tolerance. Fluid viscosity measured at operating temperature. Inlet velocity profiles derived from upstream pipe flow calculations. Input uncertainty contributions are qualitatively bounded and do not represent dominant error sources relative to the validated 8.3% MAPE. Scoped out with documented input provenance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-samples-scopeout-criteria",
      "rationale": "Statistical characterization of test sample variability is scoped out at MRL 2. The FDA generic pump geometry is a defined reference geometry without manufacturing variability by design. Experimental repeatability was assessed through triplicate runs at each operating point; coefficient of variation for NIH measurements is 4.2%, confirming adequate reproducibility. Sample-to-sample geometric variability is not applicable for the reference geometry. Scoped out per MRL 2 with repeatability data documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/equivalency-scopeout-criteria",
      "rationale": "Formal equivalency assessment between simulation and experimental input parameters is scoped out at MRL 2. Boundary conditions in the simulation are set to match measured experimental values directly: inlet flow rate matched to within 0.5%, rotational speed matched to within 0.2%, fluid viscosity matched to within 1.5%. The close correspondence between simulation inputs and experimental conditions is documented in the validation report. Scoped out per MRL 2 with quantitative correspondence documented."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cpb-mrl2-acceptance-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for the CFD hemolysis prediction model at MRL 2 is accepted based on the following structured evidence: (1) All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required Gradation 2 levels, with discretization error achieving Gradation 3. (2) The six scoped-out factors are appropriately excluded per ASME V&V 40 Table 3 for MRL 2, each with documented procedural controls or qualitative justifications. (3) Validation results demonstrate 8.3% MAPE against experimental NIH measurements across all five operating points, within the pre-specified 15% acceptance threshold. (4) The relative hemolysis index RH < 1 is confirmed for all worst-case operating conditions, satisfying the primary COU decision criterion. (5) The provenance chain is complete: experimental data traceable to calibrated instrumentation, simulation inputs traceable to CMM measurements, and hemolysis model constants traceable to peer-reviewed literature. (6) Independent peer review of simulation setup, boundary conditions, and post-processing confirmed no systematic use errors. The model is fit for the intended purpose of identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for the Class II CPB device, and the submission supports regulatory decision-making at the specified risk level.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
